=====================CHAPTER-8===========================

Class Based Components
======================

* A class based Components is a Javascript Class.
        class Profile extens React.components{
            constructor(props){
                super(props);
            };
            componentDidMount(){};

            componentDidUpdate(){};

            componentWillUnmount(){};

            render(){
                return(
                    JSX
                )
            };
        };

constructor(){} => In class based components first thing called is constructor.
                   in here we create state variables.

        How? => constructor(props){
                    this.state = {
                        count: 0,  //  0 is the initial value we pass.
                    };
                };

super(props) => Super Invokes or calls the class based components parent component by giving props as value.
                When we use super it initialize "this" in to our class based components.

componentDidMount(){}; => It render after every initial render. it is best place to
                          make api calls.
                          we can make componentDidMount(){}; as async.
            
                Ex=>  componentDidMount(){
                        asyn function getData(){
                            let data = await fetch("https.//api.com");
                            let json = await data.json();
                            this.setState({
                                json;
                            })
                        };
                        getData();
                      };

Q => why in functional based component we can not make useEffect callback function async ?
Ans => An async function always returns a Promise.
       React expects the callback passed to useEffect to return either: "Undefind" or "A cleanup function".
       but When we use asyn it get us a Promise so react Warns.
       React stores this cleanup function and executes it during unmount or before rerunning the effect.
        
        A Cleanup function => () => {
                                // cleanup
                              }

Q => Why In Class Based component we can make componentDidMount(){}; as async.
Ans => Because React never uses its return value.
       componentDidMount() can be async because React ignores its return value,
       whereas useEffect() cannot be async because React uses the callback's return value to obtain the cleanup function, 
       and an async function always returns a Promise instead of a cleanup function.


componentWillUnmount(){}; => In here we use to clean things .



                            CHAPTER-9
=========================================================================

Single Responsibility Principle
-------------------------------
    A class or function should do only one job. It should have only one reason to change.

Break down → We break down our code into small small responsibilities so our code becomes more maintainable.
Hooks are utility functions.

Custom Hook
-----------
    -Creating a custom hook is not a mandatory thing.
    -Writing code in a custom way because that makes our code:
        -> more readable
        -> more modular
        -> more reusable
How Do We Write Custom Hooks?
----------------------------
    -Hooks are normal utility functions or helper functions.
    -The best place to create these helper functions (custom hooks) is in the utils folder.
    -Always prefer a separate file for a separate hook.

Notes
-----
- Creating a hook using "use" is not mandatory in React.
- React docs recommend us to use the word "use" because when we are creating a hook, 
  most React projects set a linting process and the browser or linter throws an error 
  if we do not use the "use" keyword.

Chunking / Code Splitting / Dynamic Bundling
--------------------------------------------
    - Chunking / Code Splitting means breaking a large JavaScript bundle into smaller bundles so the browser downloads only the code needed for the current page. 
      This improves performance and reduces initial loading time.
    - When we write code by splitting it into different JS files, the bundler bundles all those files into one JS file and gives it to the browser.
      (Bundler's basic work or important work is bundling)

Problem
-------
    - The size of that JS file will increase a lot.
      We have to create smaller bundles of those files.

This process is known as:
    - Chunking
    - Code Splitting
    - Dynamic Bundling
    - Lazy Loading

EX Code
-------
        import React, { lazy, Suspense } from "react";

        const Grocery = lazy(() => import("./Grocery"));

        function App() {
        return (
            <Suspense fallback={<h1>Loading...</h1>}>
            <Grocery />
            </Suspense>
        );
        }

On Demand Loading
-----------------
    - On-demand loading means we don't want to load the Grocery component during the initial render of our app.
    - We only want to load it when the user goes to the Grocery page.

        We import it like => const Grocery = lazy();
    
lazy();
=======  
    - lazy is a function provided by React.
    - It takes a callback function as an argument.
    EX => const Grocery = lazy(() => import("./path"));

import();
========
    - We use import() inside the callback.
    - This import is different from the normal import statement.
    - import() is basically a function that takes the path of the component.

What Happens?
-------------
    - When our app initially loads in the browser, it does not load the Grocery page into memory.
    - When we navigate to the Grocery page, the browser requests another JavaScript file that contains the Grocery component.
      That page is loaded only when required.

If It Doesn't Load (Error)
--------------------------
    - A component suspended while responding to synchronous input.

Why Does This Error Happen?
---------------------------
    - When we jump to the Grocery page, it takes some time to fetch the data.
    - React Execute immediately, So During that time React tries to render the component immediately.
    - React notices that the data/component is not available yet and throws the error.
    - To handle that state, we will use Suspense.

Suspense
--------
    - Suspense is a component that comes from the React library.
    EX => import { lazy, Suspense } from "react";
    
    -We wrap our component inside Suspense.
    EX => {
            path: "/grocery",
            element: (
                <Suspense>
                <Grocery />
                </Suspense>
            ),
          };
    - We have to give this Suspense component a fallback prop.
    - fallback → We provide here what React should render when the code is not yet available.
    
    EX => <Suspense fallback={<h1>Loading</h1>}>
            <Grocery />
          </Suspense>